      "formatted_context": "=== TASK ===\nExplain the equation and method in this paper.\n\n=== RULES ===\n- (paper.start_with_intuition) Start the explanation with intuition before formalism.\n- (paper.define_symbols) Define every symbol before it is used in a derivation.\n- (paper.include_limitations) Include the limitations stated by the paper.\n- (paper.avoid_unsupported_claims) Avoid claims not supported by the paper text.\n- (paper.separate_claim_from_interpretation) Separate what the paper claims from your interpretation.\n- (paper.include_toy_example) Include a small toy example to ground the method.\n\n=== EVIDENCE ===\n[equations] Equations\nm_t = beta * m_{t-1} + (1 - beta) * ||g_t||\nhat_g_t = g_t * min(1, (lambda * m_t) / ||g_t||)\ntheta_t = theta_{t-1} - eta * hat_g_t\n\n[method] Method\nAt each step we compute the gradient g_t and its norm ||g_t||. We maintain an exponential moving average m_t of the norm. We then rescale the gradient so its norm never exceeds lambda * m_t, where lambda is a hyperparameter. The rescaled gradient is used for the parameter update.\n\n[limitations] Limitations\nGradClip adds one hyperparameter lambda that must be tuned. On clean datasets the method offers little benefit and can slightly slow convergence.\n\n[abstract] Abstract\nWe present GradClip, a method for stabilizing training of deep networks by adaptively clipping gradients. Our approach reduces variance and improves convergence on noisy datasets.\n\n[introduction] Introduction\nTraining deep networks on noisy data often diverges due to exploding gradients. Prior work uses a fixed clipping threshold. We instead adapt the threshold to the running gradient norm.\n\n[experiments] Experiments\nOn CIFAR-10-N, GradClip improves final accuracy by 2.1 points over fixed clipping. Training is more stable across five random seeds.\n",
